<div class="page">

  <div class="hero">
    <div class="hero-portrait"><img src="Assets/Personas/abdul.png" alt="Abdul"></div>
    <div class="hero-text">
      <div class="hero-eyebrow">Hearts and Minds &middot; a patient journey</div>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Abdul&apos;s journey.<br>Four acts, one record.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Abdul is 38. He and his wife both work full time; they have two young children. He occasionally walks to work, sits most of the day, and knows his diet isn&apos;t great. Heart trouble runs in the family &mdash; and he knows it. He is digitally savvy and expects to manage his health through one app.</p>
      <p class="hero-source">Drawn from the national CVKM patient journey &mdash; the original source for Abdul. The moments HomeTest carries in Year 1 are marked <span style="color:var(--amber-deep);font-weight:800;font-style:normal;">kit</span>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ribbon">
    <a href="#act1"><div class="ribbon-num">1</div><div class="ribbon-label">Stratification &amp; identification</div></a>
    <a href="#act2"><div class="ribbon-num">2</div><div class="ribbon-label">Diagnosis</div></a>
    <a href="#act3"><div class="ribbon-num">3</div><div class="ribbon-label">Treatment</div></a>
    <a href="#act4"><div class="ribbon-num">4</div><div class="ribbon-label">Long-term optimisation</div></a>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act1">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">1</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">Stratification &amp; identification</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">The system is already coming for him. He gets there first. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="abdul-a1"></span></h2>
      <div class="stage-image"><img src="Assets/Abdul Story/abdul-stage1.png" alt="Abdul checking his blood pressure with his phone camera at home" onerror="this.parentElement.style.display='none'"></div>
      <p class="stage-body">Abdul&apos;s single patient record carries his age, BMI, smoking history and a family history of heart disease and diabetes. An AI-assisted risk stratification tool reviews his notes, flags him as high risk for CVKM disease, and puts him on a contact list. <strong>But before anyone contacts him, Abdul has already logged into the NHS App</strong> to try the new blood pressure tool, using the camera on his phone. It reads 150/90 and recommends he book a CVKM Check Up &mdash; heart, kidney and circulatory health.</p>
      <p class="stage-body">Without delay, the App guides him to initiate his CVKM check. He shares the data from his smartwatch &mdash; low activity, high BP &mdash; and the App is straight with him: the camera reading will need re-testing on a medically validated cuff before anything is diagnosed.</p>
      <div class="pull-quote">
        <div class="pull-quote-text">&ldquo;I checked my BP on the NHS App because heart trouble runs in the family. The app told me to book a CVKM Check Up.&rdquo;</div>
        <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Abdul, 38 &mdash; before any clinician knew his name</div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-label">Why it matters</div>
        <div class="callout-text">Two doors opened at once: the system identified Abdul, and Abdul identified himself. Patient-initiated doesn&apos;t mean the system stops looking &mdash; it means the front door works before the letter arrives. This is the entry point most likely to scale at population level, and it has to work with no diagnosis, no open pathway, no prescription waiting.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act2">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">2</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">Diagnosis</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">His choice of venue. His kind of blood test. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="abdul-a2"></span></h2>
      <div class="stage-image"><img src="Assets/Abdul Story/abdul-stage2.png" alt="Abdul at the neighbourhood health centre having his blood pressure validated" onerror="this.parentElement.style.display='none'"></div>
      <p class="stage-body">A short digital questionnaire, then a choice: the rest of the checks can happen <strong>at home, with his GP, or at his newly opened Neighbourhood Health Centre</strong>. Abdul picks the new centre and books a slot that doesn&apos;t cost him a day&apos;s work. There, a nurse validates his BP on a proper cuff and checks for atrial fibrillation. Abdul dislikes needles &mdash; so the nurse shows him a new sampling device that sticks onto his arm and draws a small amount of blood, with less pain.</p>
      <p class="stage-body">The nurse lends him an ambulatory blood-pressure smart ring to wear for 24 hours. It confirms Stage 1 hypertension; he posts the ring back. Two days later his blood results land in the NHS App &mdash; <strong>high cholesterol and pre-diabetes</strong> &mdash; and his health centre calls to talk them through. Everything is recorded back to the GP record.</p>
      <div class="benefits">
        <div class="benefit"><div class="b-num">&minus;1</div><div class="b-label">Appointment</div><div class="b-desc">Saved at this stage alone &mdash; the screening conversation moved out of the clinic.</div></div>
        <div class="benefit choice"><div class="b-num">4 doors</div><div class="b-label">Patient route choice preserved</div><div class="b-desc">Home, GP, high-street pharmacy or the new centre. The patient picks; nobody is conscripted into digital.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="chips">
        <span class="chip kit">Kit logistics: device out, sample back, result to the record</span>
      </div>
      <div class="callout amber">
        <div class="callout-label">The Sean thread</div>
        <div class="callout-text">The stick-on sampler exists because venepuncture is a wall for some people. Abdul merely dislikes needles; for the needle-phobic, and for many people with learning disabilities, that step is where the journey ends. The adjustment that made Abdul&apos;s bloods easier is the same adjustment that makes <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Sean.html">Sean&apos;s</a> journey possible at all. Design for the hardest case and everyone&apos;s journey gets calmer.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="interlude">
    <div class="interlude-eyebrow">Later that day</div>
    <div class="interlude-title">He calls his mum.</div>
    <div class="interlude-image"><img src="Assets/Abdul Story/abdul-stage5.png" alt="Abdul on the phone to his mum in the evening" onerror="this.parentElement.style.display='none'"></div>
    <div class="interlude-body">Liz is 64. Abdul tells her about the results and how easy and fast the whole thing was. Liz thinks it sounds complicated. Abdul reassures her: if she ever needs the same tests, they can all still be done by a clinician, in person &mdash; he read it on the NHS App. The digital front door is a choice, not a toll gate. For the people it doesn&apos;t fit &mdash; Liz, and the cohorts <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Sean.html">Sean</a> stands for &mdash; the other doors stay open, and the model is built so they do.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act3">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">3</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">Treatment</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">Prescribed once. Titrated remotely. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="abdul-a3"></span></h2>
      <div class="stage-image"><img src="Assets/Abdul Story/abdul-stage3.png" alt="Abdul at his kitchen table with his delivered prescription and readings" onerror="this.parentElement.style.display='none'"></div>
      <p class="stage-body">A clinician messages Abdul through the NHS App and asks him to book an appointment. She prescribes a CVKM health programme he can access in the App, alongside a GLP-1, statins and ACE inhibitors, and refers him to the pre-diabetes prevention programme. She checks whether his smartwatch is accurate enough to monitor his BP &mdash; and it is.</p>
      <p class="stage-body">From there the cycle runs without waiting rooms. His phone uploads his BP readings automatically; the pharmacist at his health centre reviews them and adjusts his medication remotely until his BP reaches control. His electronic prescription updates and the new prescription arrives through the post. With medication reminders and logging tools doing the unglamorous work, his BP and cholesterol come under control.</p>
      <div class="benefits">
        <div class="benefit"><div class="b-num">&minus;1</div><div class="b-label">Appointment</div><div class="b-desc">The prescribing conversation happens once; the follow-ups don&apos;t need a room.</div></div>
        <div class="benefit"><div class="b-num">&minus;1&ndash;3</div><div class="b-label">Appointments across the cycle</div><div class="b-desc">Remote titration replaces the prescription shuttle until his BP reaches control.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="chips">
        <span class="chip">Remote medication titration</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="stage" id="act4">
    <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">4</div><div class="stage-bar"></div></div>
    <div class="stage-main">
      <div class="stage-eyebrow">Long-term optimisation</div>
      <h2 class="stage-title">The kit moment: a blood test that comes to the house. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="abdul-a4"></span></h2>
      <div class="stage-image"><img src="Assets/Abdul Story/abdul-stage4.png" alt="Abdul completing his home cardiometabolic self-sample kit" onerror="this.parentElement.style.display='none'"></div>
      <p class="stage-body">Eight weeks into the digital cardiometabolic programme, the clinical team message Abdul and ask him to check progress with a home blood-test self-sample. <strong>The kit comes to the house; he takes the test at home and posts it to the lab.</strong> The result confirms his risk markers have already moved in the right direction, and he&apos;s given a continuous glucose monitor to watch his blood sugars through the day. This is the HomeTest shape in miniature: kit out, sample back, result to the record, action owned by the right clinician &mdash; no clinic visit, no day off work. Today the same shape runs live on HIV testing; the CVKM configuration Abdul stands for is the future-state this journey points at.</p>
      <p class="stage-body">He carries on with a single self-service CVKM app for weight, diet and activity &mdash; rewards, local support, no switching between apps. His diabetes risk is under control. Community nurses receive alerts only when his readings drift outside his individually set levels, and reach him proactively by video call &mdash; replacing periodic reviews with attention exactly when it&apos;s needed. Abdul can pull the same cord himself and request a follow-up in the App.</p>
      <div class="benefits">
        <div class="benefit"><div class="b-num">&minus;1</div><div class="b-label">Appointment</div><div class="b-desc">The progress check posts itself to the lab; the team only reaches for him when the result says so.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="chips">
        <span class="chip kit">Home blood-test self-sample &middot; home to lab &middot; the HomeTest pattern shape</span>
        <span class="chip">Alerts replace periodic reviews</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="benefit-banner">
    <div class="bb-num">4&ndash;6</div>
    <div class="bb-text">
      <div class="bb-title">Appointments saved. Per patient. Per year.</div>
      <div class="bb-desc">With greater emphasis on self-service &mdash; and a fully digital journey saves up to <strong>6&ndash;8</strong>. Multiply that across a population and this single journey is the frontline-pressure case in miniature.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="outcomes">
    <div class="outcome">
      <div class="outcome-h">For Abdul</div>
      <div class="outcome-title">Faster, closer, his call.</div>
      <div class="outcome-body">Faster local access and clear real-time results meant earlier action on his health. He chose where each step happened &mdash; home, GP, high-street pharmacy or the new centre. Home monitoring and one personalised app keep him engaged, with clinical support behind him &mdash; and he never had to choose between his health and a day&apos;s pay.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="outcome">
      <div class="outcome-h">For the care team</div>
      <div class="outcome-title">Attention where it&apos;s needed.</div>
      <div class="outcome-body">Targeted care: clinician time concentrates on the patients who need it most. Threshold alerts and video reviews replace periodic appointments; remote titration replaces the prescription shuttle. The record stays whole &mdash; every reading, result and decision lands in one place.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="outcome">
      <div class="outcome-h">For the system</div>
      <div class="outcome-title">4&ndash;6 appointments saved. Per patient. Per year.</div>
      <div class="outcome-body">Abdul&apos;s journey saves <strong>4&ndash;6 healthcare appointments in a year</strong>, with a greater emphasis on self-service; a fully digital journey saves up to <strong>6&ndash;8</strong>. Earlier and virtual intervention reduces the cost of care and CO&#8322; emissions, and makes services genuinely accessible to working people.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="casting">
    <div class="casting-eyebrow">Where this journey sits in the model</div>
    <div class="casting-title">Abdul shows the destination. HIV proves the pattern today.</div>
    <div class="casting-body">This journey is the national CVKM vision &mdash; the future-state that patient-initiated testing is heading towards. The <strong>live patient-initiated configuration in Year 1 is HIV testing</strong>: the signed Beta that proves the pattern commercially right now. The model uses both deliberately. HIV demonstrates that a patient can order a test through the NHS App today, with no clinician request, inside a real commissioning structure; Abdul shows where that same pattern goes as CVKM screening comes onstream. The HIV-specific patient archetype is not yet named in the model. <span style="color:var(--amber-deep);font-weight:800;">&#9873;</span> See the initiation pattern in the <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Anatomical.html">Anatomical comparison</a>, and <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Abdul.html">Abdul&apos;s role in the model</a>.</div>
